# Competitors

## Direct (same product space, GSC-based monitoring)
- **SEOmonitor**: comprehensive but expensive ($300+/mo), oriented at agencies. Slow on AI Overviews coverage.
- **Accuranker**: solid SERP tracker, weak on decay/alerting layer.
- **Nightwatch**: mid-market, dashboard-heavy, weak API.

## Indirect (same audience, different product)
- **ahrefs.com/blog**: comprehensive, well-researched, but corporate voice and slow to publish on AI search topics. Their guides are often 3,000+ words where 1,500 would do.
- **searchengineland.com**: news-driven, not how-to. Good for citations on Google announcements.
- **searchengineroundtable.com**: Barry Schwartz, near-realtime news, light on tactics. Cite for SERP feature and update timing.
- **backlinko.com**: Brian Dean's brand. Very strong on traditional SEO, weak on AI-era tactics. Use sparingly.

## Their content moat (do NOT duplicate without a fresh angle)
- Comprehensive "complete guide to <X>" megaposts (Ahrefs, Backlinko)
- Annual "ranking factors" studies (Backlinko, SEMrush)
- "Beginners guide to SEO" content (everyone)
- Generic "how to do keyword research" tutorials

## Their content gap (where we should focus)
- AI fan-out coverage as a ranking input (almost nobody covers this concretely)
- Content decay detection workflows (mentioned by everyone, executable by almost no one)
- Practical Claude Code / AI agent automation for SEO (almost zero quality coverage as of May 2026)
- Three Kings audit at scale (we have a tool for this; nobody else writes about it)
- AI Overviews citation worthiness signals (everyone speculates, few measure)
